ce:section.ce:para:
The micro-morphologies of WHP and the prepared catalysts were investigated through SEM. Fig. 2
                        A shows that BiOCl has an irregularly layered structure with a grain thickness of about 392 nm and an average grain size of about 1.12 μm, and the stacking direction is extremely disorderly. WHP presents large and thin sheets, and the thickness of grain is about 236 nm (Fig. 2B). Compared with the reference BiOCl, as shown in Fig. 2C, the grain thickness and average grain size of the 1% sample is only 262 nm and 1.08 μm, respectively, which signifies that addition of WHP will cause the thickness and average grain size of BiOCl nanosheets to decrease. However, no CQDs was clearly observed by SEM. In order to confirm the existence of CQDs, HRTEM images were observed, and the results were depicted in Fig. 2D, two lattice fringes with different spacing were found in 1%CQDs/BiOCl to be 0.19 nm and 0.33 nm, assigning to the (200) and the (002) crystal plane of BiOCl and CQDs, separately [25]. Meanwhile, CQDs are uniformly distributed on BiOCl at the multiples of 20 nm (Fig. 2E), and further magnification can confirm the exposure of the (002) crystal plane of CQDs. Fig. 2F shows that BiOCl has an obvious single crystal structure through selective electron diffraction (SAED) [48]. Additionally, the uniform distribution of CQDs on the BiOCl can be observed by EDS mapping (Fig. 2G and Fig. 2H), These obvious observations solidly attest that CQDs have been successfully existed on BiOCl. Therefore, after the modification of CQDs, the reduction of grain size of BiOCl can shorten the migration time of photoexcited electrons from the bulk to surface, thus improving the separation rate of photoinduced e-/h+ pairs and promoting the photocatalytic performance, so as to achieving the purpose of environmental protection by degradation of the pollutants [49]. For photocatalytic reaction, the surface of catalyst is the place where the reaction takes place, therefore, adsorption property and specific surface area (SBET) of all the prepared photocatalysts were obtained through BET test. Fig. S1 exhibits that N2 absorption-desorption isotherms of the 1% sample and the reference BiOCl have no obvious hysteresis loops, suggesting that almost no pores in the sample, which is consistent with the SEM image observation results of the sample. However, it is obvious that decoration of CQDs can dramatically increase SBET of the samples (Table 1
                        ). In general, high SBET can increase the contact area with pollutants and expose more reaction active space, which is conductive to improve the photocatalytic efficiency [50]. However, combined with the photocatalytic performance tests, the activity is not proportional to the value of SBET, which can be assigned to the active sites only accounts for a small part of the total surface area, and the catalytic reaction usually occurs on these active sites.

Photocatalytic performance of CQDs/OVs-BiOCl photocatalysts for RhB degradation under visible light illustration was evaluated and exhibited in Fig. 7
                        A. Firstly, the photolysis of RhB was performed prior to the photocatalytic degradation experiment in order to exclude the instability of the selected simulated pollutant. Eventually, the photolysis of RhB exposed to visible light is 5%, considering the measurement error, which can be ignored. After establishing the adsorption-desorption equilibrium, 300 W Xe lamp (λ> 420 nm) was turned on. The destruction efficiency of RhB over the reference BiOCl is 64% after 80 min illumination. The degradation efficiency of RhB on CQDs/OVs-BiOCl samples significantly enhances. The degradation efficiency of RhB on the 1% sample is the highest, the removal efficiency of RhB is 91% after reaction. Impressively, the photocatalytic efficiency of BiOCl begins to decrease as the increasing of CQDs content. Although the successful modification of CQDs on BiOCl surface facilitates the transfer of photogenerated electrons from BiOCl to CQDs, overloading of CQDs on BiOCl surface will seriously limit the light assimilation and block the original active site. Simultaneously, photocatalytic degradation rate of RhB on the photocatalysts was examined and depicted in Fig. 7B. The concentration change of RhB with reaction time follows pseudo-first-order kinetics. In detail, the formula is -ln(Ct/C0) = kt, and the value of k is the pseudo-first-order rate constant. The rate constant of RhB over the 1% sample is the highest (0.0286 min-1), which is 2.6 folds of that over the reference BiOCl (0.01114 min-1). Fig. 7C illustrates the spectrum evolution of RhB on 1%CQDs/OVs-BiOCl. Obviously, the highest peak appears at 554 nm, and the peak intensity declines with the extension of irradiation time and the peak shifts to a low wavelength, indicating that RhB has been gradually mineralized into small molecules, which can be further confirmed by TOC experiment. To show the versatility of photocatalytic materials, a strong carcinogenicity and stable PFOA was used as a simulated pollutant to further examine the degradation property of all the photocatalysts under a mercury lamp irradiation and the test results were shown in Fig. S4. To highlight the difference in photocatalysis, degradation kinetics of PFOA on the reference BiOCl and the 1% samples was depicted in Fig. 7D. The detoxification rate of PFOA on BiOCl is 76%, and the detoxification rate of PFOA on 1%CQDs/OVs-BiOCl is about 11% higher than that on BiOCl, which strongly supports that BiOCl material is a reliable photocatalyst for defluorination of PFOA. Detoxification of PFOA on the reference BiOCl and 1%CQDs/OVs-BiOCl was fitted by a pseudo-first order kinetic (Fig. 7E). The detoxification rate constant of PFOA by the reference BiOCl and 1%CQDs/OVs-BiOCl is 0.01351 min-1 and 0.01875 min-1, separately, indicating that the photocatalytic performance of 1% sample for PFOA is 1.4 folds of that of the reference BiOCl. Considering that PFOA is colorless, clearly, dye sensitization is not the primary factor in boosting the photocatalytic performance of CQDs/OVs-BiOCl materials. Fig. 7F shows that the defluorination rate of PFOA on the reference BiOCl and the 1% sample is 32.1% and 35.8%, respectively, indicating that CQDs/OVs-BiOCl material is an effective photocatalyst for degradation of PFOA. In a word, the prepared CQDs/OVs-BiOCl photocatalyst has high degradation capacity towards pollutants and good universality. The stability of CQDs/OVs-BiOCl photocatalysts is also a pivotal factor for practical application. RhB was selected as a simulated pollutant, and the kinetic curve was obtained after 5 cycles of degradation of RhB over the 1% sample (Fig. 7G). 1%CQDs/OVs-BiOCl can maintain high activity, and the degradation rate of RhB has no significant change. Fig. 7H shows the crystal structure of 1%CQDs/OVs-BiOCl before and after the cycle. The results show that the main peaks are consistent with the standard card of BiOCl (JCPDS: 06–0249), no appear other peaks or no peaks have shift, indicating that the prepared CQDs/OVs-BiOCl samples have outstanding stability, which provides a strong foundation for practical application. Besides, photocatalytic performance of 1% sample was compared with other reported photocatalysts to further highlight the performance superiority of the photocatalysts prepared by this method (Table 2
                        ), obviously, 1%CQDs/OVs-BiOCl possesses outstanding photoactivity in degradation of RhB and defluorination of PFOA, which solidly attests that water hyacinth powder-assisted in-situ fabrication of BiOCl is an excellent strategy to ameliorate the photocatalytic performance of BiOCl.
